<div class="content-section">
<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can blood tests confirm perimenopause?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Not reliably. Hormone levels fluctuate too widely during the perimenopause transition for a single draw to be diagnostic. FSH is sometimes cited as a signal, but a single elevated value isn&#8217;t conclusive. The more important value of testing is ruling out thyroid disease and iron deficiency (which overlap symptomatically with perimenopause), establishing a cardiovascular risk baseline, and tracking hormonal trends over time &#8212; not getting a one-draw verdict.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What blood tests should a woman get at 40?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Beyond the standard lipid panel: <a href="/biomarkers/apob">ApoB</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/lipoprotein-a">Lp(a)</a> (once), <a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin">fasting insulin</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/homocysteine">homocysteine</a>, a full hormone panel (<a href="/biomarkers/estradiol">estradiol</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/fsh">FSH</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/progesterone">progesterone</a>, testosterone), full thyroid (TSH + free T3 + free T4 + TPO antibodies), <a href="/biomarkers/ferritin">ferritin</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d">Vitamin D</a>, and RBC magnesium. Most are not included in standard primary care.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How does perimenopause affect cardiovascular risk?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Estrogen supports arterial flexibility, favorable lipid profiles, and lower inflammation. As estrogen declines, <a href="/biomarkers/apob">ApoB</a> tends to rise, <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP</a> climbs, and the overall cardiovascular risk profile can shift substantially &#8212; often without any clinical warning. Women who were at low risk in their 30s may find their risk profile meaningfully elevated by their mid-40s. This is why ApoB and hsCRP become essential measurements at this life stage.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why is fasting insulin important for women over 40?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Research suggests a significant proportion of women develop some degree of insulin resistance during perimenopause. <a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin">Fasting insulin</a> rises years before HbA1c moves into the prediabetes range. A woman can have completely normal glucose and HbA1c while fasting insulin is already elevated &#8212; a state of early insulin resistance that worsens cardiovascular risk and promotes visceral fat accumulation. It&#8217;s almost never ordered in standard primary care.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is thyroid disease more common in women over 40?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Yes &#8212; substantially. Thyroid disorders, particularly Hashimoto&#8217;s thyroiditis and subclinical hypothyroidism, are far more common in women and prevalence rises with age. Symptoms overlap heavily with perimenopause. <a href="/biomarkers/tsh">TSH</a> alone can appear normal in early Hashimoto&#8217;s. A complete workup &#8212; TSH + free T3 + free T4 + TPO antibodies &#8212; is the minimum when these symptoms are present.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do I need a doctor to order these tests?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">No. Direct-to-consumer services like <a href="/reviews/ulta-lab-tests">Ulta Lab Tests</a> allow any adult to order all of these markers without a physician&#8217;s referral &#8212; you purchase online, visit a Quest Diagnostics draw site, and receive results in 24&#8211;48 hours. Not available in New York, New Jersey, Rhode Island, or Hawaii.</div>
</div>
